00:44:26.630 --> 00:44:33.390
is an entirely different matter. Not unique
to the United States by any means. In fact,

00:44:33.390 --> 00:44:38.400
and this will be a little sobering to you,
there are organizations that rank the countries

00:44:38.400 --> 00:44:41.740
of the world in terms of their free speech
and press and so on.

00:44:41.740 --> 00:44:46.430
The United States and the organization that
you're most familiar with called Freedom House,

00:44:46.430 --> 00:44:52.079
started by Eleanor Roosevelt back just after
World War II. And they rank all the countries

00:44:52.079 --> 00:44:57.670
in the world by how free they are every year.
Their most recent report ranked the United

00:44:57.670 --> 00:45:01.499
States not first, not second, tied for 24th.

00:45:01.499 --> 00:45:02.559
[laughter]

00:45:02.559 --> 00:45:09.109
With the Czech Republic, behind countries
like Estonia and Jamaica and so on. And ranked

00:45:09.109 --> 00:45:15.819
right up at the top in freedom of the press,
in particular, are all the Scandinavian countries.

00:45:15.819 --> 00:45:21.690
Iceland and Finland seem to trade off One
and Two year after year. It's all of them.

00:45:21.690 --> 00:45:25.890
Part of it has to do with the structure of
our media. Part of it has to do with the decline

00:45:25.890 --> 00:45:32.539
of the newspaper industry here. In Finland,
for example, a great majority of the population

00:45:32.539 --> 00:45:36.539
reads on paper two newspapers a day.

00:45:36.539 --> 00:45:42.690
Unheard of in this country. They just care
more about those values than we seem to. Yes,

00:45:42.690 --> 00:45:43.690
sir.

00:45:43.690 --> 00:45:52.490
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #3: The state of Tennessee
recently passed a bill that--. The state of

00:45:52.490 --> 00:45:58.779
Tennessee recently passed a bill that would
fine a person who posts an image that's online

00:45:58.779 --> 00:46:03.900
that someone finds offensive. Do you have
any remarks about that? Or do you think that

00:46:03.900 --> 00:46:05.369
bill is long for this world?

00:46:05.369 --> 00:46:10.240
&gt;&gt;William Bennett Turner: I'm not familiar
with the Tennessee bill. If all it does is

00:46:10.240 --> 00:46:19.359
say you can't post an image that is offensive,
that is on its face unconstitutional. As I

00:46:19.359 --> 00:46:24.289
say, offensiveness is protected by the First
Amendment.

00:46:24.289 --> 00:46:31.819
Many, many cases saying that the fact that
something is offensive, is highly offensive,

00:46:31.819 --> 00:46:41.450
doesn't deprive the speech of First Amendment
protection. And that law will not survive

00:46:41.450 --> 00:46:47.059
scrutiny for more than a minute.

00:46:47.059 --> 00:46:52.630
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #4: You mentioned in
the Reno v. ACLU case that part of the ruling

00:46:52.630 --> 00:46:56.980
was based on internet not sharing the unique
properties of broadcast.

00:46:56.980 --> 00:46:57.980
&gt;&gt;William Bennett Turner: Right.

00:46:57.980 --> 00:47:00.670
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #4: Do you foresee
a return to that question now that internet

00:47:00.670 --> 00:47:03.780
is increasingly access through potentially
regulated spectrum?

00:47:03.780 --> 00:47:07.589
&gt;&gt;William Bennett Turner: Potentially regulated
spectrum such as--

00:47:07.589 --> 00:47:11.180
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #4: I mean like cell
phone, wireless connection.

00:47:11.180 --> 00:47:20.499
&gt;&gt;William Bennett Turner: No, I don't. I think
one of the benefits of having a totally corporate

00:47:20.499 --> 00:47:27.019
business-oriented majority on the Supreme
Court these days is that they are anti-regulation.

00:47:27.019 --> 00:47:33.970
The five conservatives on the court all came
to Washington as part of the Reagan revolution,

00:47:33.970 --> 00:47:41.069
"Let's get government off our backs." And
one of the items that the Reagan Administration

00:47:41.069 --> 00:47:47.099
attacked right on was the Fairness Doctrine,
which used to be imposed by the FCC on licensed

00:47:47.099 --> 00:47:48.099
broadcasters.

00:47:48.099 --> 00:47:55.390
They got rid of that. They abandoned that.
And I don't detect any sentiment on the court

00:47:55.390 --> 00:48:10.009
for endorsing legislation now that would return
the internet to any kind of regulation about

00:48:10.009 --> 00:48:16.989
what can be and what can't be done in the
way of content. One slightly worrisome thing

00:48:16.989 --> 00:48:27.150
is the convergence factor, as you mentioned,
where the various media converge and become

00:48:27.150 --> 00:48:28.150
one.

00:48:28.150 --> 00:48:35.970
We get everything out of one place--a device,
or whatever it is. That opens up the argument

00:48:35.970 --> 00:48:41.829
that there ought to be the government regulation
of the FCC, for example. They still police

00:48:41.829 --> 00:48:51.740
indecency. CBS got fined several hundred thousand
dollars for showing a nanosecond of Janet

00:48:51.740 --> 00:48:55.329
Jackson's breast at the halftime show of Super
Bowl.

00:48:55.329 --> 00:49:00.529
The FCC's still in that business. They may
be put out of it this year in a case that's

00:49:00.529 --> 00:49:08.609
pending in New York, but the FCC is still
policing the air waves. It comes over the--.

00:49:08.609 --> 00:49:18.339
Not cable. They don't police content on cable,
but on over-the-air radio and television broadcast.

00:49:18.339 --> 00:49:24.989
The FCC's still in that business. As media
converge, would they likely extend that? I

00:49:24.989 --> 00:49:27.180
don't think so. I don't think they could get
away with it.

00:49:27.180 --> 00:49:33.650
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #5: I got the impression
that you feel that the First Amendment should

00:49:33.650 --> 00:49:39.670
have protected WikiLeaks. And I was wondering--.
I don't know if that's true, but I was wondering

00:49:39.670 --> 00:49:47.839
if there, is there any type of government
information that you think it shouldn't protect

00:49:47.839 --> 00:49:51.720
for divulging? For example, suitcase atomic
weapons or whatever.

00:49:51.720 --> 00:49:56.769
&gt;&gt;William Bennett Turner: Yeah, sure. No,
obviously there are real, genuine needs for

00:49:56.769 --> 00:50:06.000
government to keep some secrets. Unfortunately,
government doesn't do a very good job on keeping

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:07.609
secrets.

00:50:07.609 --> 00:50:15.180
And they use that classified stamp in a libertine
way. I mean, they just classify so much, the

00:50:15.180 --> 00:50:22.450
classification becomes meaningless. If Private
Bradley Manning, who's the alleged leaker

00:50:22.450 --> 00:50:29.859
to WikiLeaks, was in fact the leaker, he had
a security clearance that gave him access

00:50:29.859 --> 00:50:32.670
to all of those classified documents.

00:50:32.670 --> 00:50:39.309
He shared that clearance with 500 thousand
other people. How do you expect to keep a

00:50:39.309 --> 00:50:47.980
secret that 500 thousand people have access
to? You're right in thinking WikiLeaks ought

00:50:47.980 --> 00:50:53.760
to have, that I think, WikiLeaks ought to
have a First Amendment defense to violating

00:50:53.760 --> 00:50:59.430
the Espionage Act, but that depends on facts
that I don't know.

00:50:59.430 --> 00:51:04.711
Wouldn't you like to hear the conversation
between Assange and Manning? Because I think

00:51:04.711 --> 00:51:12.770
a lot depends on how WikiLeaks got the information.
If they got the files over the transom as

00:51:12.770 --> 00:51:19.029
we used to say, passively, they didn't do
anything. They were just dumped in their lap.

00:51:19.029 --> 00:51:27.299
And then published them on the internet. That's
just like the New York Times in the Pentagon

00:51:27.299 --> 00:51:35.900
Papers case. But if Assange and WikiLeaks
actively solicited the leaks, paid the leaker,

00:51:35.900 --> 00:51:42.980
provided software assistance to the leaker
and so on, then probably they can be charged

00:51:42.980 --> 00:51:48.999
with conspiracy, which is a prosecutor's favorite.

00:51:48.999 --> 00:51:53.430
And they're more like Ellsberg in that situation.
They're the actual--. They stand in the same

00:51:53.430 --> 00:52:03.130
shoes as the actual government employee who
betrayed his trust. But we don't know what

00:52:03.130 --> 00:52:07.859
conversation, if any. I mean, Assange denies
that there was any conversation.

00:52:07.859 --> 00:52:13.480
He denies knowing who Manning was until his
name was published in the press later on.

00:52:13.480 --> 00:52:21.079
So good is WikiLeaks encryption technology,
even the people at WikiLeaks don't know who

00:52:21.079 --> 00:52:22.460
they're dealing with.

00:52:22.460 --> 00:52:25.759
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Well, on that note, thank
you very much for coming.

00:52:25.759 --> 00:52:26.239
[applause]

